If you're looking at some of the internal stuff, and it's all doing it, it looks like it's using Pyrefly to generate some of these things.

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:27.240
Maybe?

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:27.960
I don't know.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:28.360
Interesting.

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:32.340
That's pretty much it.

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:36.480
Just as if you want to look at anything in the docs, but with types.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:37.560
There you go.

00:17:38.300 --> 00:17:40.600
Like what does a slice take?

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:44.960
Oh, slice takes a, you know, well, it's going to be like.

00:17:45.620 --> 00:17:46.520
It's an any, any.

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:47.220
Not too much.

00:17:47.380 --> 00:17:47.600
Any, any.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:52.820
But there's somewhere probably an interval of or something.

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:53.720
Who knows?

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:55.160
Yeah.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:56.820
Pretty cool.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:57.540
I like this idea.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:58.160
That's great.

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:07.740
I think these, these kinds of things are powerful too, because especially if you're doing any sort of AI thing, you would say, you know, you ask, is it something that's like, what are you doing?

00:18:07.780 --> 00:18:08.340
You have no idea.

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:09.160
Thing.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:11.020
Read the docs or check this out.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:15.080
Or I'm going to, you know, and if it has type information, that really gives it a lot more to work with.

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:16.740
Yeah.

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:26.300
And also because like, that, that the docs, the Python docs are really for us, but type shed is really not for us.

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:32.880
So the kind of the idea to combine the information in type shed and present it as the docs.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.560
It's pretty kind of, it's kind of a clever thing.

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:36.280
Yeah.

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:36.920
It's very clever.

00:18:36.920 --> 00:18:45.180
And also if you're doing something kind of like something built in, you can look at, you know, look at what the types are with that and try to match it.

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:46.300
Yeah, definitely.

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:46.920
Definitely.

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:49.000
All right.

00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:50.160
Shall we keep with our theme?

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:52.920
Or yeah, of, of theme swapping.

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:54.040
So.

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:54.260
Yeah.

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.240
Like to just keeping the theme going.

00:18:56.320 --> 00:18:58.300
So I want to talk about databases some more.

00:18:59.660 --> 00:19:00.020
Okay.

00:19:00.020 --> 00:19:07.460
And, and ORMs, but from a different perspective this time a little bit in the sense that I wrote an article.

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:13.480
The article I want to talk about is raw plus DC database pattern, a retrospective.

00:19:13.620 --> 00:19:15.240
This is, this is pretty interesting.

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:21.340
But in order to talk about, let me just talk about the design pattern that I publish real quick.

00:19:21.340 --> 00:19:25.860
So people maybe didn't read that article or they didn't listen a couple episodes ago or something.

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:27.440
Right.

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:41.380
So my thesis is there's a couple of reasons why depending on maybe smaller ORM libraries, it's not that great of an idea necessarily.

00:19:41.380 --> 00:19:55.860
One is if that thing goes unsupported, you've got a good chunk of your application and a foundational portion of it that is tied to this potentially unsupported thing.

00:19:56.240 --> 00:19:57.260
So make that concrete.

00:19:57.440 --> 00:20:00.680
Talk Python training, when I created it, was based on Mongo Engine.

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:06.500
And that was a up and coming super nice query syntax.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:12.240
Also models exactly the Django ORM, by the way, by Oxide, like Oxide ORM.

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:21.220
So a lot of the queries in there looked very much like they were Django, but they were object-based going to MongoDB, right?

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:23.280
So that's great.

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:31.160
But fast forward 10 years and that thing's had a couple of releases that like changed the readme in five years.

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:40.660
And for reasons maybe I'll get to later, like another episode is I wanted to switch this to async.

00:20:41.080 --> 00:20:52.320
I wanted to switch Talk Python training to async, but this older ORM library was not ever, ever going to move to adopt an async model.

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:53.140
Right.

00:20:53.140 --> 00:20:56.860
Even if it doesn't throw away its synchronous model, like have an async option.

00:20:57.060 --> 00:21:04.420
Like, no, I mean, if it's all that's happening is like a couple of readmes are getting updated, there's no way they're rewriting the whole thing to be async.

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:05.020
You know what I mean?

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:06.360
Yeah.

00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:09.020
And it's also probably a scratch your own itch sort of thing.

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:13.000
If the current project does what they need it to do, why update it?

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:13.500
Yeah.

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:17.120
And they're not obligated to, but I'm also not obligated to keep using it.

00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:17.320
Right.

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:25.500
So that's number one is like, is there a more stable base?

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:31.080
And the stable base is whatever the core database driver package is.

00:21:31.100 --> 00:21:39.500
In this case, it's PyMongo, but, you know, could be just the core one from the Postgres team talking to Postgres with Python.

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:40.040
Right.

00:21:40.100 --> 00:21:43.000
Like that's what all these ORMs are based on often anyway.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:48.840
I mean, oxide ORM is not quite probably based on the Rust version that the Postgres team provides or whatever.

00:21:48.980 --> 00:21:49.120
Right.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:50.800
So something like that.

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:52.520
So that's one.

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:58.160
The other one, the raw part has to do with this theory that I have that.

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:08.820
Talking to when you're working with agentic AI, they know frameworks, but what they really know super well is the foundational stuff.

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:14.100
Like they probably know SQL model, but they really know SQL, you know?

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:14.560
Yeah.

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:21.440
They probably know Mongo Engine a little bit, but they really know just queer, like raw MongoDB queries.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:32.640
And so that's the idea is like, like what if we just had a data access layer that was just raw queries and it returned some kind of rich classes like data classes?

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:33.140
Yeah.

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:39.460
Now, before people email me, because I talked about this on Reddit and like three fourths of the comments were, why aren't you using Pydantic?

00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:40.760
You could use Pydantic here.

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:43.320
Do you know that you're using data classes when you could use Pydantic?

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:44.420
You have no type.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:47.040
Like, yes, sure.

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:49.980
You want to call it raw plus Pydantic and use Pydantic instead?

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:52.440
It's literally the same thing.

00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:54.140
You're totally welcome to do that, right?

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:56.500
I just wanted something simple.

00:22:56.980 --> 00:23:07.880
I found like my dream of Pydantic, like in Beanie and other, these ORMs or SQL model is you've got this ORM and it returns Pydantic models.

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:13.280
And maybe you've got FastAPI and you could just like take the thing straight from the database and send it out over the API.

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:14.580
And how amazing would that be?

00:23:14.580 --> 00:23:24.000
I almost never was able to take the database model and return it directly as an API response.

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:26.860
And so you're always like transforming them anyway.

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:32.200
And so I ended up showing like I just don't need, I don't need a Pydantic all the way down.

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:34.320
Like Pydantic at the boundaries was good for me.

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:35.040
Okay.

00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:39.620
So all that's so I can tell you about my retrospective.

00:23:39.620 --> 00:23:46.800
So I wrote up this thing where I rewrote Talk Python training.

00:23:47.020 --> 00:23:50.840
Now Python Bytes is already using this, so it already gets this benefit.

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:54.240
But I did this for Talk Python training, the courses.

00:23:55.240 --> 00:23:59.520
I said, well, let me just put it into practice and see how it goes and if it's any better.

00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:01.640
So I came with pictures, Brian.

00:24:01.740 --> 00:24:02.540
Look at these pictures.

00:24:04.520 --> 00:24:07.320
Mongo Engine, the raw plus DC pattern.

00:24:07.600 --> 00:24:09.260
It's almost 2x.

00:24:09.620 --> 00:24:13.620
More requests per second for the same hardware, the same everything else.

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:16.160
Just switching this out.

00:24:16.820 --> 00:24:21.640
And the bonuses, you get a much more stable library to program against.

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:23.480
And AI is really good.

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:29.020
If you say, hey, AI, hey, Claude, create me an update function to do this thing.

00:24:29.260 --> 00:24:31.080
And it can do that better, right?

00:24:31.140 --> 00:24:35.920
It has a more, much, much, much, much more training information to do that with.

00:24:36.080 --> 00:24:37.780
And you get 2x performance.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:44.760
And even when you're doing 2x the number of requests, you still get quite a bit faster response time.

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:46.620
That's pretty cool.

00:24:47.160 --> 00:24:47.320
Yeah.

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:48.020
Pretty neat, right?

00:24:48.400 --> 00:24:48.580
Yeah.

00:24:48.700 --> 00:24:49.460
And you scroll down.

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:55.840
Another bonus is actually about 10% less memory usage as well.

00:24:55.840 --> 00:24:58.940
That's good.

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:05.760
Because apparently the ORM and the classes that it uses and the tracking and whatever just hangs on to junk more.

00:25:06.140 --> 00:25:06.600
I don't know.

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:08.760
I mean, I'm still using classes, right?

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:13.000
But for whatever reason, it's just quite a bit less memory usage.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:18.080
So I think that's turning out to be a pretty promising way to go.

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:19.740
Yeah.

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:20.380
Yeah.

00:25:20.420 --> 00:25:21.780
I expect more about this stuff later.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:23.820
So I can't resist.

00:25:24.820 --> 00:25:28.940
If you've already considered data classes, have you considered adders instead?

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:31.000
Thank you.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.440
I want something built in.

00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:36.760
I want something with fewer dependencies.

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:38.740
Data classes are built in.

00:25:38.860 --> 00:25:44.480
Pydantic and adders are both separate packages, right?

00:25:44.820 --> 00:25:45.020
Yeah.

00:25:45.020 --> 00:25:52.320
The benefit for choosing adders has to be big enough that it justifies taking on another dependency.

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:55.280
So I talked about data class of wizards.

00:25:55.440 --> 00:26:02.340
So for this kind of stuff, I'm like, if I need to read and parse and validate data, I'm doing data class of wizards along with data classes.

00:26:02.480 --> 00:26:04.480
But people are certainly welcome to choose adders.

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:05.860
They're welcome to choose Pydantic.

00:26:05.940 --> 00:26:06.280
Pydantic, yeah.

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:07.520
They all work good in this model.

00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:08.380
Yeah.

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:21.020
Well, and especially to give other people for projects that already have Pydantic for other reasons, that makes sense also.

00:26:21.100 --> 00:26:21.540
Yeah, yeah.

00:26:21.580 --> 00:26:22.020
Absolutely.

00:26:22.700 --> 00:26:23.040
Absolutely.

00:26:24.020 --> 00:26:25.300
All right.

